1
00:00:05,320 --> 00:00:06,200
Stanford University

2
00:00:09,620 --> 00:00:10,060
Okay.

3
00:00:12,080 --> 00:00:12,680
All right,

4
00:00:12,680 --> 00:00:14,300
let's talk about time-like,

5
00:00:14,300 --> 00:00:15,100
space-like,

6
00:00:15,100 --> 00:00:15,860
and light-like.

7
00:00:16,059 --> 00:00:16,620
For that,

8
00:00:16,620 --> 00:00:18,000
we just go back to special relativity.

9
00:00:19,300 --> 00:00:20,960
Let's spell out what that means.

10
00:00:20,960 --> 00:00:29,920
And special relativity is a metric.

11
00:00:30,140 --> 00:00:32,600
We've discussed this metric many times.

12
00:00:32,860 --> 00:00:34,740
We call it proper time.

13
00:00:35,240 --> 00:00:37,910
d tau squared is the square of

14
00:00:37,910 --> 00:00:40,580
the proper time of some little interval.

15
00:00:40,780 --> 00:00:42,540
And as you remember,

16
00:00:42,540 --> 00:00:45,480
it's dt squared minus dx squared

17
00:00:45,480 --> 00:00:48,420
minus dy squared minus dz squared.

18
00:00:48,640 --> 00:00:49,400
Okay.

19
00:00:53,240 --> 00:00:54,220
And if we want to

20
00:00:54,220 --> 00:00:55,200
put the speed of light in,

21
00:00:55,200 --> 00:00:57,680
sometimes I'll put the speed of light in.

22
00:00:57,740 --> 00:01:01,110
The reason I put the speed of light in sometimes is

23
00:01:01,110 --> 00:01:04,480
to keep track of what's small and what's big under certain circumstances.

24
00:01:04,980 --> 00:01:05,780
For example,

25
00:01:05,780 --> 00:01:06,740
if you want to study,

26
00:01:06,740 --> 00:01:08,700
if you want to go to the nonrelativistic limit,

27
00:01:08,700 --> 00:01:10,560
the limit where everything is moving slowly,

28
00:01:11,280 --> 00:01:15,450
then it's good to put back the speed of light because it keeps track in that case

29
00:01:15,450 --> 00:01:19,620
of the fact that the speed of light is much bigger than any other velocities in the problem.

30
00:01:20,080 --> 00:01:20,940
So let me put it back.

31
00:01:20,960 --> 00:01:22,120
I'm going to put it in for the moment.

32
00:01:22,400 --> 00:01:25,450
I'll put it in and

33
00:01:25,450 --> 00:01:28,500
take it out under various circumstances.

34
00:01:29,200 --> 00:01:30,460
It goes in like that,

35
00:01:30,460 --> 00:01:31,320
1 over c squared.

36
00:01:35,560 --> 00:01:39,640
And if d tau squared is greater than 0,

37
00:01:41,440 --> 00:01:41,960
now,

38
00:01:41,960 --> 00:01:43,360
of course,

39
00:01:43,360 --> 00:01:44,960
the square of a real

40
00:01:44,960 --> 00:01:46,560
number is always greater than 0,

41
00:01:46,680 --> 00:01:48,800
but d tau squared is not defined

42
00:01:48,800 --> 00:01:50,920
by being the square of a real number.

43
00:01:50,920 --> 00:01:53,120
It's defined by this combination over here.

44
00:01:53,540 --> 00:01:55,380
And it can be positive or negative,

45
00:01:55,380 --> 00:01:59,700
depending on whether the x squared plus the y squared plus the

46
00:01:59,700 --> 00:02:04,020
z squared is bigger than dt squared or smaller than dt squared.

47
00:02:05,060 --> 00:02:06,510
I said the x squared plus

48
00:02:06,510 --> 00:02:07,960
the y squared plus the z squared,

49
00:02:07,960 --> 00:02:10,169
but I meant the x squared over c squared

50
00:02:10,169 --> 00:02:12,380
plus the y squared over c squared and so forth.

51
00:02:12,660 --> 00:02:13,520
But in any case,

52
00:02:13,520 --> 00:02:15,320
if d tau squared is greater than 0,

53
00:02:16,300 --> 00:02:18,600
then the little element here

54
00:02:18,600 --> 00:02:20,900
is said to be t squared.

55
00:02:21,840 --> 00:02:24,220
So it's got more time than it has space,

56
00:02:24,220 --> 00:02:24,820
so to speak.

57
00:02:25,180 --> 00:02:27,460
This part is bigger than this part.

58
00:02:27,880 --> 00:02:29,460
And that can be described

59
00:02:29,460 --> 00:02:31,040
in terms of a light cone.

60
00:02:31,380 --> 00:02:32,360
Remember the light cone?

61
00:02:32,680 --> 00:02:36,540
The light cone looks like that.

62
00:02:37,420 --> 00:02:39,580
And the boundaries of the light cone,

63
00:02:39,580 --> 00:02:40,460
the cone itself,

64
00:02:40,460 --> 00:02:43,200
are the places where dt squared...

65
00:02:43,200 --> 00:02:43,740
Let's,

66
00:02:43,740 --> 00:02:45,160
for the moment,

67
00:02:45,160 --> 00:02:46,700
I don't want the c squared there.

68
00:02:47,380 --> 00:02:47,980
Are...

69
00:02:49,400 --> 00:02:51,690
dt squared equals dx squared

70
00:02:51,690 --> 00:02:53,980
plus dy squared plus dz squared.

71
00:02:54,220 --> 00:02:55,600
That's called light-like.

72
00:02:56,460 --> 00:02:59,720
If dt squared is bigger than dx

73
00:02:59,720 --> 00:03:02,980
squared plus dy squared plus dz squared,

74
00:03:03,120 --> 00:03:05,210
it means the little vector lies

75
00:03:05,210 --> 00:03:07,300
in the interior of the cone,

76
00:03:07,300 --> 00:03:08,920
like that.

77
00:03:09,340 --> 00:03:12,060
It could also be lying in the backward direction.

78
00:03:12,620 --> 00:03:14,060
In either case,

79
00:03:14,700 --> 00:03:15,640
a little interval,

80
00:03:15,640 --> 00:03:16,600
or a vector.

81
00:03:16,720 --> 00:03:18,000
Let's speak about a vector in general.

82
00:03:18,220 --> 00:03:20,850
A vector in general is time-like if its time component is

83
00:03:20,850 --> 00:03:23,480
bigger than the sums of the squares of the space components.

84
00:03:25,440 --> 00:03:25,960
Okay,

85
00:03:25,960 --> 00:03:26,880
that's time-like.

86
00:03:31,480 --> 00:03:34,820
Space-like is exactly the opposite.

87
00:03:35,640 --> 00:03:36,800
It's dt squared,

88
00:03:36,800 --> 00:03:38,940
d tau squared less than 0.

89
00:03:39,360 --> 00:03:40,480
And in that case,

90
00:03:40,480 --> 00:03:43,680
we usually define another quantity,

91
00:03:43,680 --> 00:03:44,920
ds squared,

92
00:03:45,640 --> 00:03:47,520
which is just a negative of d tau squared,

93
00:03:47,920 --> 00:03:48,700
and it,

94
00:03:48,700 --> 00:03:49,380
by definition,

95
00:03:49,380 --> 00:03:52,510
is dx squared plus dy squared

96
00:03:52,510 --> 00:03:55,640
plus dz squared minus dt squared.

97
00:03:56,460 --> 00:03:58,480
It's the same object except for the relative,

98
00:03:58,480 --> 00:03:59,100
or the different,

99
00:03:59,100 --> 00:03:59,900
or the minus sign.

100
00:04:00,600 --> 00:04:02,930
Space-like vectors are ones for which

101
00:04:02,930 --> 00:04:05,260
ds squared is bigger than 0,

102
00:04:05,780 --> 00:04:07,560
d tau squared is less than 0,

103
00:04:07,700 --> 00:04:12,980
and space-like vectors lie outside the light cone.

104
00:04:13,579 --> 00:04:14,140
Finally,

105
00:04:14,140 --> 00:04:15,640
there are light-like vectors.

106
00:04:15,780 --> 00:04:16,660
This is space-like.

107
00:04:17,959 --> 00:04:18,980
And finally,

108
00:04:18,980 --> 00:04:20,240
there are light-like vectors.

109
00:04:20,579 --> 00:04:23,959
And light-like vectors are the ones for which ds

110
00:04:23,959 --> 00:04:27,340
squared equals dx squared plus dy squared plus dz squared.

111
00:04:27,820 --> 00:04:30,260
Those are the trajectories of light rays,

112
00:04:30,580 --> 00:04:33,180
and they lie in the cone.

113
00:04:33,300 --> 00:04:36,020
They lie in the surface of the cone itself.

114
00:04:36,760 --> 00:04:38,000
Those are the three kinds

115
00:04:38,000 --> 00:04:39,240
of vectors that you can have.

116
00:04:40,520 --> 00:04:41,080
Um,

117
00:04:43,840 --> 00:04:45,200
just for a moment,

118
00:04:45,200 --> 00:04:47,480
consider what it would mean

119
00:04:48,679 --> 00:04:50,340
if there were two negative,

120
00:04:50,340 --> 00:04:50,900
sorry,

121
00:04:50,900 --> 00:04:53,280
two positive signs and two negative signs

122
00:04:53,280 --> 00:04:56,640
instead of one positive sign and three negative signs.

123
00:04:57,120 --> 00:04:57,780
Somehow,

124
00:04:57,780 --> 00:05:01,880
this would correspond to two time directions.

125
00:05:04,219 --> 00:05:04,880
Uh,

126
00:05:04,880 --> 00:05:07,400
that doesn't mean anything in physics.

127
00:05:07,600 --> 00:05:08,080
In physics,

128
00:05:08,080 --> 00:05:09,760
there are never two time directions.

129
00:05:10,520 --> 00:05:12,820
There are always one time,

130
00:05:12,820 --> 00:05:13,620
and three space.

131
00:05:13,960 --> 00:05:14,160
Now,

132
00:05:14,160 --> 00:05:16,320
can you imagine a world with two time...

133
00:05:16,320 --> 00:05:16,920
I can't.

134
00:05:16,920 --> 00:05:17,200
Frankly,

135
00:05:17,200 --> 00:05:17,860
I can't.

136
00:05:17,860 --> 00:05:19,660
I can't imagine what it would

137
00:05:19,660 --> 00:05:21,460
mean to have two different time directions.

138
00:05:21,780 --> 00:05:24,300
And we will simply take the view that,

139
00:05:24,300 --> 00:05:24,520
uh,

140
00:05:24,520 --> 00:05:26,020
that that's not an option.

141
00:05:26,420 --> 00:05:31,060
There is always one time-like direction in the metric here,

142
00:05:31,220 --> 00:05:32,400
and three space-like.

143
00:05:32,580 --> 00:05:34,690
But that doesn't mean that there's

144
00:05:34,690 --> 00:05:36,800
a unique direction which is time-like.

145
00:05:37,160 --> 00:05:38,920
There are many time-like directions,

146
00:05:39,060 --> 00:05:40,900
pointing within this light cone here.

147
00:05:41,120 --> 00:05:42,800
The invariant state of the light cone

148
00:05:42,820 --> 00:05:45,980
is a statement about the metric tensor.

149
00:05:46,560 --> 00:05:47,800
The metric tensor,

150
00:05:47,800 --> 00:05:49,140
we can write this in the form

151
00:05:49,140 --> 00:05:51,740
d tau squared is equal to

152
00:05:51,740 --> 00:05:54,340
g mu nu with a minus sign

153
00:05:54,340 --> 00:05:56,880
dx mu dx nu.

154
00:05:57,080 --> 00:05:59,780
The minus sign is a convention.

155
00:06:04,520 --> 00:06:07,250
It's always defined so that g

156
00:06:07,250 --> 00:06:09,980
mu nu dx mu dx nu

157
00:06:11,540 --> 00:06:14,290
goes with the space-like vectors

158
00:06:14,290 --> 00:06:17,040
having a positive sign here.

159
00:06:17,800 --> 00:06:18,440
Incidentally,

160
00:06:18,440 --> 00:06:19,920
one other thing I'll just remind you.

161
00:06:20,560 --> 00:06:20,720
Um,

162
00:06:20,720 --> 00:06:26,600
the proper time along a trajectory like this

163
00:06:26,600 --> 00:06:28,900
is a measure of what a

164
00:06:28,900 --> 00:06:31,200
clock along a trajectory ticks off.

165
00:06:31,740 --> 00:06:34,440
Proper time is a kind of time.

166
00:06:34,640 --> 00:06:36,840
It's the time read off by a moving clock.

167
00:06:38,699 --> 00:06:39,780
Proper distance,

168
00:06:39,780 --> 00:06:41,080
the s squared,

169
00:06:41,300 --> 00:06:45,400
proper distance along a space-like surface

170
00:06:45,400 --> 00:06:48,500
is distance measured by a meter stick.

171
00:06:49,520 --> 00:06:50,920
So proper distance,

172
00:06:50,920 --> 00:06:51,800
the s squared,

173
00:06:52,000 --> 00:06:53,520
or the square root of the s squared,

174
00:06:53,680 --> 00:06:55,200
really is a distance,

175
00:06:55,440 --> 00:06:57,460
and proper time really is a time.

176
00:06:57,940 --> 00:06:58,480
Uh,

177
00:06:58,480 --> 00:07:00,440
and keep that in mind.

178
00:07:00,800 --> 00:07:01,340
Okay,

179
00:07:01,340 --> 00:07:01,760
so,

180
00:07:01,760 --> 00:07:02,380
uh,

181
00:07:02,380 --> 00:07:05,460
this is our definition of the metric.

182
00:07:05,460 --> 00:07:07,840
And for the case here that we've written,

183
00:07:08,060 --> 00:07:14,140
the metric can be written in terms of a matrix.

184
00:07:14,740 --> 00:07:15,700
And let's see,

185
00:07:15,700 --> 00:07:17,340
the matrix is minus one,

186
00:07:18,120 --> 00:07:18,680
zero,

187
00:07:18,680 --> 00:07:19,320
zero,

188
00:07:19,320 --> 00:07:19,780
zero,

189
00:07:19,780 --> 00:07:20,840
zero,

190
00:07:20,840 --> 00:07:21,360
one,

191
00:07:21,360 --> 00:07:22,020
zero,

192
00:07:22,020 --> 00:07:22,680
zero,

193
00:07:22,680 --> 00:07:23,680
zero,

194
00:07:23,680 --> 00:07:23,900
zero,

195
00:07:23,900 --> 00:07:24,180
zero,

196
00:07:24,180 --> 00:07:24,220
one,

197
00:07:24,220 --> 00:07:24,700
zero,

198
00:07:24,700 --> 00:07:25,640
zero,

199
00:07:25,640 --> 00:07:26,040
zero,

200
00:07:26,040 --> 00:07:26,320
zero,

201
00:07:26,320 --> 00:07:26,520
one.

202
00:07:27,100 --> 00:07:28,560
It's called eta mu nu.

203
00:07:29,120 --> 00:07:30,600
It's like the Kronecker delta,

204
00:07:30,600 --> 00:07:32,240
except it has a minus sign.

205
00:07:33,140 --> 00:07:33,700
Okay,

206
00:07:33,700 --> 00:07:35,440
this thing has obvious,

207
00:07:35,460 --> 00:07:37,400
obviously three positive eigenvalues.

208
00:07:37,520 --> 00:07:38,080
It's a matrix.

209
00:07:38,440 --> 00:07:40,210
It has three positive

210
00:07:40,210 --> 00:07:41,980
eigenvalues and one negative eigenvalue.

211
00:07:42,260 --> 00:07:44,340
And that's the invariant story.

212
00:07:44,600 --> 00:07:45,340
That's the story,

213
00:07:45,480 --> 00:07:48,200
not that there's only one time direction,

214
00:07:49,439 --> 00:07:53,460
but that there is one negative eigenvalue here.

215
00:07:55,820 --> 00:07:58,920
And a metric which would have two negative eigenvalues,

216
00:07:59,120 --> 00:08:00,720
or three negative eigenvalues,

217
00:08:00,720 --> 00:08:01,940
would have more than one time.

218
00:08:02,160 --> 00:08:04,320
And we just don't even think about that.

219
00:08:04,320 --> 00:08:06,830
That's something that physics does not

220
00:08:06,830 --> 00:08:09,340
seem to have made use of,

221
00:08:09,380 --> 00:08:10,600
two negative times.

222
00:08:11,540 --> 00:08:12,100
Okay,

223
00:08:12,100 --> 00:08:14,260
so that's space-like,

224
00:08:14,260 --> 00:08:14,860
time-like,

225
00:08:14,860 --> 00:08:15,640
light-like,

226
00:08:15,640 --> 00:08:16,240
and so forth.

227
00:08:23,080 --> 00:08:24,200
More generally,

228
00:08:24,200 --> 00:08:26,660
it could be in flat space,

229
00:08:26,920 --> 00:08:28,580
but certainly in curved space,

230
00:08:28,580 --> 00:08:29,640
curved space-time,

231
00:08:30,219 --> 00:08:31,780
the metric tensor G,

232
00:08:31,780 --> 00:08:33,860
the metric tensor cannot be chosen

233
00:08:33,860 --> 00:08:36,120
to be equal to this eta symbol here.

234
00:08:36,640 --> 00:08:38,080
It's a general function,

235
00:08:38,080 --> 00:08:39,580
G mu nu of X.

236
00:08:42,760 --> 00:08:44,800
But G mu nu of X

237
00:08:44,800 --> 00:08:46,840
cannot just be any old thing.

238
00:08:47,240 --> 00:08:48,700
At every point,

239
00:08:48,700 --> 00:08:49,680
at every X,

240
00:08:49,680 --> 00:08:51,460
there's a matrix.

241
00:08:51,840 --> 00:08:52,640
At every X,

242
00:08:52,640 --> 00:08:53,160
there's a matrix,

243
00:08:53,160 --> 00:08:54,200
every point.

244
00:08:54,540 --> 00:08:55,920
And at every X,

245
00:08:55,920 --> 00:09:00,940
there must be one negative eigenvalue

246
00:09:00,940 --> 00:09:02,700
and three positive eigenvalues.

247
00:09:02,700 --> 00:09:03,700
Wherever you are,

248
00:09:03,700 --> 00:09:05,100
standing there,

249
00:09:05,280 --> 00:09:08,640
you should experience a world with one time direction

250
00:09:08,640 --> 00:09:09,800
and three space directions.

251
00:09:10,439 --> 00:09:10,760
Or,

252
00:09:10,760 --> 00:09:11,780
more exactly,

253
00:09:11,780 --> 00:09:14,200
one negative eigenvalue and three positive.

254
00:09:15,420 --> 00:09:16,060
Okay,

255
00:09:16,060 --> 00:09:18,080
so what that means,

256
00:09:19,479 --> 00:09:21,920
what that means is that every point in space

257
00:09:22,660 --> 00:09:26,260
has a light cone associated with it.

258
00:09:26,380 --> 00:09:26,920
Now,

259
00:09:26,920 --> 00:09:28,800
I'm drawing it sort of tipped and tilted.

260
00:09:29,459 --> 00:09:32,160
That reflects the fact that the coordinates themselves

261
00:09:32,700 --> 00:09:34,940
might be wavy and curved and so forth.

262
00:09:36,520 --> 00:09:37,200
So,

263
00:09:37,200 --> 00:09:38,220
as you move around,

264
00:09:38,580 --> 00:09:42,860
because the coordinates and also the metric tensor

265
00:09:42,860 --> 00:09:44,920
might be varying from place to place,

266
00:09:45,320 --> 00:09:50,720
the light cone might have an apparent tendency

267
00:09:50,720 --> 00:09:54,680
to look different in different places.

268
00:09:56,500 --> 00:09:58,420
But that is just because,

269
00:09:59,400 --> 00:10:00,080
because,

270
00:10:00,080 --> 00:10:03,560
because as you move around in space,

271
00:10:03,820 --> 00:10:05,920
the metric tensor may change from place to place

272
00:10:05,920 --> 00:10:09,240
and the coordinates change from place to place.

273
00:10:09,780 --> 00:10:10,300
Alright,

274
00:10:10,300 --> 00:10:11,100
so at every point,

275
00:10:11,100 --> 00:10:11,880
there's a light cone.

276
00:10:12,240 --> 00:10:14,860
There's a notion of light,

277
00:10:14,860 --> 00:10:15,460
a space,

278
00:10:15,600 --> 00:10:16,300
a time-like,

279
00:10:16,300 --> 00:10:16,980
excuse me,

280
00:10:17,020 --> 00:10:20,340
time-like vectors inside the light cone,

281
00:10:20,620 --> 00:10:23,120
space-like vectors outside the light cone,

282
00:10:23,840 --> 00:10:25,000
and light-like,

283
00:10:25,000 --> 00:10:27,220
the motion of light rays

284
00:10:27,900 --> 00:10:31,800
along the edge or the cone itself.

285
00:10:32,080 --> 00:10:33,340
The cone is the surface.

286
00:10:33,500 --> 00:10:34,740
When you have an ice cream cone,

287
00:10:35,960 --> 00:10:37,330
the ice cream on the inside

288
00:10:37,330 --> 00:10:38,700
is not part of the cone.

289
00:10:39,140 --> 00:10:41,060
The cone is the surface itself,

290
00:10:41,060 --> 00:10:41,520
